-- China shares rise the most in a month, helped by auto and liquor makers
-- By Grace Li
-- Mon Jul 14, 2014 03:09AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 14 (Reuters) - China shares posted their best daily gain in a month on Monday as carmakers extended recent gains after the government announced a fresh boost for the sector.

Chinese liquor makers also rose strongly. The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> ended up 1 percent at 2,066.65 points, a four-week high, while the CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings climbed 1.1 percent. It was the best day for both indexes since June 10. In Shanghai, SAIC Motor Corp <600104.SS> rose 2.4 percent, following Friday's 1.6 percent gain, to close at its highest since May 2013. BYD <002594.SZ> leapt 3.9 percent in Shenzhen.  In a notice published on Sunday, China urged government officials to use more electric and plug-in hybrid cars as part of its drive to cut pollution. It aims to put 5 million such vehicles on the road by 2020.[ID:nL4N0PP0QM] Kweichow Moutai <600519.SS>, the country's leading high-end liquor producer, jumped 5.6 percent, the top boost on both indexes. Another sector leader Wuliangye Yibin <000858.SZ> spiked 5.9 percent.